I've tracked the code all the way down into the apply effect, directX does indeed seem to be setting the vector into ConstantBuffers with the value shown in this image:

![alphabug](https://f.cloud.github.com/assets/10628/866527/d2cb187c-f68d-11e2-9c72-765ec8c9b4cc.PNG)
(W=alpha, x is red, y is green, z is blue)

The shader I am using is very very simple:

``` hlsl
PIXEL_OUT PixelProgram(VERTEX_OUT IN)
{
    PIXEL_OUT OUT;

    OUT.Color = gDrawColor;

    return OUT;
}
```

I am set for AlphaBlend.
If i set alpha to 1.0 it looks solid as it should.
0.5 looks a little less solid,
and 0.0 looks as u see above...

I would have expected 0.0 to be completely transparent?

Though it does seem to work if i multiply the alpha directly into the color as well.

``` c#
    OUT.Color = gDrawColor;
    OUT.Color *= a;
```

Just using:

``` C#
    OUT.Color = gDrawColor;
    OUT.Color.a = 0;
```

results in:
