I'm not sure what XNA did with this kind of shader though.

I am using the content pipeline to rebuild a font asset using the font name and size.  The problem I'm having is that when I use it to rebuild a sprite font, the program RAM usage jumps from 136MB to 2100MB.  According to the output of the program:

```
Font reloaded with RAM 115MB.
Font reloaded with RAM 116MB.
Font reloaded with RAM 118MB.
...
Start font rebuild at 128MB.
Font data was 0MB.
Font data is 0MB.
Font reloaded with RAM 2184MB.
End font rebuild at 2184MB.
```

It doesn't appear that the SpriteFont itself is actually large, as the resulting binary data is under a MB in size.  But whatever the content pipeline does results in 2GB of RAM being used!

The font asset class has `ReloadFont` and `RebuildFont` functions:

``` csharp
public void ReloadFont()
{
    if (this.m_AssetContentManager != null && this.FontData != null)
    {
        using (var stream = new MemoryStream(this.FontData))
        {
            Console.WriteLine("Font reloaded with RAM " + (Process.GetCurrentProcess().WorkingSet64 / 1024 / 1024) + "MB.");
            this.m_AssetContentManager.SetStream(this.Name, stream);
            this.m_AssetContentManager.Purge(this.Name);
            this.Font = this.m_AssetContentManager.Load<SpriteFont>(this.Name);
            this.m_AssetContentManager.UnsetStream(this.Name);
        }
    }
}

public void RebuildFont()
{
    Console.WriteLine("Start font rebuild at " + (Process.GetCurrentProcess().WorkingSet64 / 1024 / 1024) + "MB.");
    if (this.FontData != null)
        Console.WriteLine("Font data was " + (this.FontData.Length / 1024 / 1024) + "MB.");
    var data = this.m_ContentCompiler.BuildSpriteFont(
        this.FontName,
        this.FontSize,
        0,
        false);
    if (data != null)
    {
        this.FontData = data;
        Console.WriteLine("Font data is " + (this.FontData.Length / 1024 / 1024) + "MB.");
        this.ReloadFont();
    }
    Console.WriteLine("End font rebuild at " + (Process.GetCurrentProcess().WorkingSet64 / 1024 / 1024) + "MB.");
}
```

The implementation of `BuildSpriteFont` is:

``` csharp
public byte[] BuildSpriteFont(string fontName, float size, float spacing, bool useKerning)
{
    var chars = new List<char>();
    for (int i = 0; i < 256; i++)
        chars.Add((char)i);
    var description = new FontDescription(
        fontName,
        size,
        spacing,
        FontDescriptionStyle.Regular,
        useKerning,
        chars);
    var manager = new PipelineManager(null, null, null);
    var dictionary = new OpaqueDataDictionary();
    var processor = manager.CreateProcessor("FontDescriptionProcessor", dictionary);
    var context = new DummyContentProcessorContext(TargetPlatform.Linux);
    var content = processor.Process(description, context);
    var compiler = new Microsoft.Xna.Framework.Content.Pipeline.Serialization.Compiler.ContentCompiler();
    var temp = Path.GetTempFileName();
    try
    {
        using (var stream = new FileStream(temp, FileMode.Open, FileAccess.Write))
        {
            compiler.Compile(stream, content, TargetPlatform.Windows, GraphicsProfile.Reach, false, Environment.CurrentDirectory, Environment.CurrentDirectory);
        }
        using (var stream = new FileStream(temp, FileMode.Open, FileAccess.Read))
        {
            stream.Position = 0;
            using (var reader = new BinaryReader(stream))
            {
                var result = reader.ReadBytes(Int32.MaxValue);
                File.Delete(temp);
                return result;
            }
        }
    }
    finally
    {
        File.Delete(temp);
    }
}
```

I don't know a lot about the content pipeline, but surely it shouldn't be using this much RAM to compile content?

The Vector3.Min/Max calls in the BoundingBox.CreateFromPoints method is making this method very slow. The compiler can probably inline these functions, but we can make this method about 5X faster with a simple change:

```
    private static readonly Vector3 MaxVector3 = new Vector3(float.MaxValue);
    private static readonly Vector3 MinVector3 = new Vector3(float.MinValue);

    public static BoundingBox CreateFromPoints(IEnumerable<Vector3> points)
    {
        if (points == null)
            throw new ArgumentNullException();

        // TODO: Just check that Count > 0
        bool empty = true;
        Vector3 minVec = MaxVector3;
        Vector3 maxVec = MinVector3;
        foreach (Vector3 ptVector in points)
        {
            minVec.X = (minVec.X < ptVector.X) ? minVec.X : ptVector.X;
            minVec.Y = (minVec.Y < ptVector.Y) ? minVec.Y : ptVector.Y;
            minVec.Z = (minVec.Z < ptVector.Z) ? minVec.Z : ptVector.Z;

            maxVec.X = (maxVec.X > ptVector.X) ? maxVec.X : ptVector.X;
            maxVec.Y = (maxVec.Y > ptVector.Y) ? maxVec.Y : ptVector.Y;
            maxVec.Z = (maxVec.Z > ptVector.Z) ? maxVec.Z : ptVector.Z;

            empty = false;
        }
        if (empty)
            throw new ArgumentException();

        return new BoundingBox(minVec, maxVec);
    }
```

The current `BoundingBox.CreateFromPoints()` looks like this...

```
public static BoundingBox CreateFromPoints(IEnumerable<Vector3> points)
{
```

While this is convenient because it can work with anything it.... it generates garbage because of the generic iterator loop.

We should add a List<Vector3> specialization of this function because list iteration is garbage free:

```
public static BoundingBox CreateFromPoints(List<Vector3> points)
```
